 Euroregions: Dynamics of a Cross-Border Sectoral Field -- t12. Galicia and the Norte Region of Portugal: An Experience of Cross-Border Cooperation on the Portugal–Spain Border -- t13. Cooperation and Cross-Border Conflicts in Cerdanya (Spanish–French Border) in Early Twenty-First-Century Environmental and Economic Crises -- t14. The Evolving Cross-Border Cooperation of Nouvelle Aquitaine–Euskadi–Navarre (Western Pyrenees Boundary): Multiple Actors and Aims of Cooperation -- t15. Conclusion: Comparing Cross-Border Governance in North America and Europe: Conclusions -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn North America and Europe, cross-border governance arrangements have provided formal and informal frameworks to support cross-border cooperation. Analysing how these frameworks have emerged, the ways in which they have become institutionalized, and the processes by which they change is fundamental. Moreover, these frameworks are increasingly challenged by border securitization, thus limiting or jeopardizing decades of cross-border cooperative governance and coordinated public policies. Agents and Structures in Cross-Border Governance offers a series of case studies that explore these complex dynamics. To understand a range of cross-border governance frameworks, this collection addresses such topics as infrastructure development and management, resource sharing, regional politics, economics, security, human rights, the environment, culture, and community. The book explains how cross-border governance schemes have sought to mitigate some of the negative consequences of border security policies, allowing readers to discern how concrete national power struggles between federal/national and subnational governments unfold in border areas. In a world increasingly impacted by climate change and more recently the COVID-19 pandemic, Agents and Structures in Cross-Border Governance sheds light on the ongoing complexity of cross-border governance and offers lessons to help mitigate these challenges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBorderlandsvCase studies. 0aCanadianxAmerican Border RegionvCase studies. 7aLAW / Comparative.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aEurope.  aMexico.  aNorth America.  aUnited States.  aborder security.  aborders.  acomparitive politics.  across-border cooperation.  agovernance.  ainternational cooperation.  ainternational relations.  apolitics.1 aBerzi, Matteo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamonita, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCancela Outeda, Celso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrea-Cabrera, Guadalupe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Pamela L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupeyron, Bruno , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDupeyron, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurà-Guimerà, Antoni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonrad, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendoza Cota, Jorge Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoferini, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoferini, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOliveras González, Xavier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPayan, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPayan, Tony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPerrin, Thomas, econtributo